10.1 Backup Strategy
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

PostgreSQL (RDS):
  Automated Backups:
    Frequency:  Every 6 hours
    Retention:  30 days
    Type:       AWS RDS snapshots
    Region:     Primary + Cross-region copy

  Point-in-Time Recovery:
    WAL archiving enabled
    Recovery point: any point in last 30 days
    Recovery time: < 30 minutes

Redis (ElastiCache):
  AOF persistence enabled
  Snapshot: Every 1 hour
  Retention: 7 days

S3 Files:
  Versioning: Enabled on all buckets
  Cross-region replication: To me-south-1
  Glacier transition: After 90 days

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
10.2 Recovery Scenarios
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

SCENARIO 1: Single Service Down
  Detection: Health check fails → PagerDuty P2
  Resolution:
    Kubernetes auto-restart (30 sec)
    If persistent → new pod scheduled
    If node failure → new node added
  RTO: < 2 minutes
  RPO: 0 (stateless services)

SCENARIO 2: Database Failure
  Detection: RDS health check → P1 alert
  Resolution:
    Multi-AZ auto-failover (< 60 sec)
    Read replica promoted if needed
  RTO: < 2 minutes
  RPO: < 5 seconds (transaction loss)

SCENARIO 3: Entire Region Down
  Detection: CloudWatch alarms → P1
  Resolution:
    DNS failover to secondary region
    RDS restore from cross-region snapshot
    EKS cluster in secondary region
    S3 replication already active
  RTO: < 1 hour
  RPO: < 1 hour

SCENARIO 4: Data Corruption / Deletion
  Detection: Application errors, user reports
  Resolution:
    Point-in-time recovery to pre-corruption
    Targeted table restore from snapshot
    Audit log analysis for root cause
  RTO: < 4 hours
  RPO: < 6 hours (last backup)

SCENARIO 5: Security Breach
  Response Team:
    1. Isolate affected services immediately
    2. Rotate ALL secrets and credentials
    3. Force logout ALL active sessions
    4. Forensic analysis of audit logs
    5. Notify affected users within 72h (PDPL)
    6. Regulatory notification if required
  RTO: 4-24 hours (depending on scope)

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
10.3 Runbook — Critical Incidents
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

ON-CALL ROTATION:
  Primary:   CTO / Lead Engineer
  Secondary: Senior Backend Engineer
  Escalation: CEO for P1 > 2h unresolved

INCIDENT SEVERITY:
  P1 CRITICAL:
    → Auth Service down (users can't login)
    → Database unreachable
    → Security breach detected
    Response: 15 minutes, all hands

  P2 MAJOR:
    → Any core service down > 5 min
    → Error rate > 5%
    → Payment processing down
    Response: 30 minutes

  P3 MINOR:
    → Performance degradation
    → Non-critical feature broken
    Response: 4 hours

COMMUNICATION:
  Internal: Slack #incidents channel
  Users: Status page (status.majlis.io)
  Major incidents: In-app banner
